\subsection{Ordinary Differential Equations}
An Ordinary Differential Equation (ODE) describes the relationship between a function and its derivates with respect to a single, independent variable (in our case, time). A general first order Intial Value Problem (IVP) is given by:
\begin{equation} 
\frac{dy}{dt} = f(t,y) \quad y(t_0) = y_0,
\end{equation}
where $f(t,y)$ is a known function with $y(t)$ representing the unknown solution.

In many practical applications, especially when $f(t,y)$ is non-linear, analyatical solutions can be extremely difficult or impossible to obtain. Thus, the solution must be approximated by discretising time into steps of size $h$, producing a sequence of approximations for $\{y_n\}$ at discrete points $t_n = t_0 + nh$.
